  If Someone Asks Tough Questions

  "Why not use Kubernetes built-in resource metrics?"
  → Kubernetes shows current CPU/memory but can't analyze patterns over time. A container using 0.1% CPU could be a
  lightweight service OR a zombie. You need temporal analysis (30-60 minute windows) to tell the difference.

  "What happens if the detector itself becomes a zombie?"
  → It's excluded from its own analysis via the --exclude-namespaces flag. It runs in a separate namespace (zombie-detector).

  "Can this scale to large clusters?"
  → Yes. It queries Prometheus (which already scales with the cluster) and analyzes each container independently. Resource   
  usage is minimal: 100m CPU, 256Mi memory.

  "Why 60-point threshold for zombie?"
  → It means at least one rule must trigger strongly (with the boost formula). This prevents false positives while catching  
  containers that clearly match zombie patterns.



